@node INTRODUCTION "Introduction"
---<Introduction to FrillyCDPro>---

  FrillyCDPro v1.5r2
  -+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+


  Announcing "FrillyCDPRO"

  What is it?  Well, it's a CD/ZIP/HD door for Maxs BBS systems.  
  Why "FrillyCD" then if it can handle all the different formats? Well,
  quiet simple really.  FrillyCDHDZIP sounds stupid, and one of my other
  doors is called FrillyAxs (FrillyAccess) - so I couldn't use that.

  It came about because I saw a CD door a while back (MaxSuperCD) which 
  was completely unable to get into drawers which had spaces as part of
  their filenames (such as "MOD DIRECTORY").  I thought I could do it - 
  had a go, and this is the result.  So, if you think it looks "similar"
  to MaxSuperCD then I suppose it does.

  I also wasn't impressed that you had to pay Ł5.00 for the only decent CD
  door around at the time (KewlCDPro) - Honestly, the BBS scene is
  pratically dead in the water as it is - charging for doors is a bit lame.

  This door does EVERYTHING KewlCDPro does - and MORE, plus it's FREE!!!




                             @{"MAIN MENU" Link MAIN}


@endnode
@node INSTALLATION "Installation"
---<Installing FrillyCDPro>---


	To install the door, simply UNPACK the archive, and then copy all
  the files from inside to that place on your Hard/Drive.  If this Drawer
  doesn't exist - then just MOVE the complete un-archived program over, 
  which will create the drawer.  To achieve this task - I recommend either
  Directory Opus, or go to the shell, and use LHA, like so:

        CLI> C:Lha x FrillyCDPro-v1.5r2.lha DOORS:

  If you downloaded this file from the Aminet - your achive is called a
  different name - to meet their rules about LONG filenames.  In that case
  follow this example, and IGNORE the above CLI instruction...

	CLI> C:Lha x FrillyCDPro.lha DOORS:


  Now - simply run the program as a Max Door function 34, like so:


  Key  Function  Extra  Lo Acc  Hi Acc  Path/Filename/Extra...
    ?        34      0       ?       ?  DOORS:FrillyCDPro/FrillyCDPro xx M


  Set up whatever key selection, low and high access you would like,
  then replace the "xx" after FrillyCDPro with the DRIVE you wish the
  program to access (ie CD0:), the last character on this line ("M") should
  be either an "=" EQUALS (=) sign, to tell the program you are using the
  standard "Maxs" BBS, or "+" to tell the program that you are using Max
  Pro BBS.  Actually the Door doesn't give a monkeys if you DON'T include 
  the "M" part - but Door coders seem to frown on you for not using it...


  For more details about using the EXTRA features in FrillyCDPro see the
  @{"Standard Usage" Link USAGE} and @{"Advanced Usage" Link REGISTERED} section.



                            @{"MAIN MENU" Link MAIN}


@endnode
@node USAGE "Standard Usage"
---<Using FrillyCDPro - UNREGISTERED USERS>---


See also the @{"Advanced Usage" Link REGISTERED} section.


  Passing Parameters to FrillyCDPro:


  You can tell FrillyCDPro which device to access by giving it the NAME
  like so:

	"FrillyCDPro CD0:" The CD0: bit tells the program to access CD0:,
  so CD1: does CD1: and ZIP0: handles ZIP disks.  You can be really BORING
  and just tell it "DH0:" or whatever, but bear in mind, that if you do this
  then users will be able to download EVERYTHING on that HARD DRIVE.... 
  You have been warned.  


  If you do NOT give the program a parameter - it defaults to CD0:



  When the program is loaded, and working - you can press some keys to
  navigate your way around.

	UP goes UP a FILE, 		DOWN goes DOWN a FILE, 
	LEFT goes UP a DIRECTORY,	RIGHT goes DOWN a DIRECTORY
	ENTER goes "inside" the selected Directory flagged by YELLOW ansi
	P goes to the "parent" Directory,

	M will MARK or UNMARK files (only in the current Directory)
	D will DOWNLOAD your Marked files (flagged in MAGENTA ansi)
	Q will QUIT the Door, and return control to Maxs BBS


  An UNREGISTERED copy of FrillyCDPro can ONLY access the first 14 files 
  from each directory, and can only access the first 14 directorys on any
  device (CD/ZIP/HD etc).  Registered users have no such restriction.



  ANSI configuration.....
  -----------------------

  The files "DOWNLOAD", "ERROR", "GIMME_GIMME", "HACKED", "INSTRUCTIONS"
  and "NO_ACCESS" can all be edited even by UNREGISTERED users.  These
  files can be found in the DOORS/FrillyCDPro/ANSI directory.  The names
  are obvious really - but here's a quick run-through.

  1. DOWNLOAD - used when a LOCAL LOGIN tries to DOWNLOAD files
  
  2. ERROR - Should NEVER see this screen, means an ERROR has occured
  
  3. GIMME_GIMME - This pops up if there is NO object in the drive the door
  has been setup to access (posh talk for NO CD in CD-ROM tray, or NO ZIP
  in ZIP bay...)
  
  4. HACKED - You should NEVER, EVER see this :-)  A sysop has tried to
  HACK the keyfile, or he is using a "borrowed" keyfile...
  
  5. INTRUCTIONS - Tells you what KEYS do WHAT in the program (KEEP THE TOP
  LINE EMPTY - IT'S USED TO DISPLAY THE VERSION NUMBER OF FRILLYCDPRO...)
  
  6. NO_ACCESS - Pops up when a User tries to access an object with higher
  access than he has (ie, if u wanna make ya CD access 10000 then only
  SYSOPS will be able to view it, and everyone else will be greeted with the
  NO_ACCESS screen...)



                             @{"MAIN MENU" Link MAIN}


@endnode
@node REGISTERED "Advanced Usage"
---<Using FrillyCDPro - REGISTERED USERS>---


See also the @{"Standard Usage" Link USAGE} section.


Advanced Configuartion: (ONLY for registered users)

 The CDChanger and Access.Levels files should be placed inside 
 DOORS:FrillyCDPro


  More than ONE CD/ZIP on your System.....
  ----------------------------------------

  Create an EMPTY file called 'CDChanger'. The door will then display ALL 
  CD-Roms with CD's inside them, and let your user select which one to 
  access.


  Restricting Access to CD's/ZIP's etc.....
  -----------------------------------------
 
  Create a file called Access.Levels, make the FIRST line the NAME of the
  object you are accessing (get this from the TOP of the FrillyCDPro screen)
  Make sure you CHANGE any SPACE characters to UNDERLINES.  So "My CD"
  would become "My_CD".  Then on the NEXT line, give the MINIMUM access
  required to look at the contents of that object.

  If you have the CD-Changer bit enabled, it lets the user see the NAME of
  the devices.  However - when he selects one, it then checks the access
  and decides whether to let them in or not ;-)



  ANSI configuration screens.....
  -------------------------------

  The files "FIND_WHAT" and "FOUND" in the DOORS/FrillyCDPro/ANSI directory
  can be altered for use by registered users.  The most IMPORTANT one is
  "FIND_WHAT" which is used when the user actually performs the search.
  Simply create an ANSI - and at the end of it, insert the SCREEN POSITION
  to return to.  It then returns to this position to input the SEARCH data.

  "FOUND" can be altered - although DO NOT go BELOW line 7 on screen, as
  lines below this are used to print the FOUND matches, and TOTAL NUMBER OF
  MATCHES.


  Extra REGISTERED user options from INSIDE the door.....
  -------------------------------------------------------

	8 goes UP a page (FILES),	2 goes DOWN a page (FILES)
	4 goes UP a page (DIRECTORYS)	6 goes DOWN a page (DIRECTORYS)
	S Search Option - you can also MARK/UNMARK files from the search
	V View the FILE_ID.DIZ from inside an LHA or LZX file
  	R Root Directory Keypress



Thinking of Registering.... See the @{"Registration" link Registration} section



                             @{"MAIN MENU" Link MAIN}


@endnode
@node COPYRIGHT "Copyright"
---<Copyright/Credits>---


    FrillyCDPro 1.5 is (C) Copyright Dave Till 1999/2000
    ----------------------------------------------------


    FrillyCDPro was "inspired" by MaxSuperCD by Colin Wilson (although I 
    must point out that NO SOURCE CODE from that program was used, tis all 
    my very own creation....)  If I had a penny for every time some idiot
    assumed I'd just adapted/ripped off Colin's source I'd be a very rich 
    man.

    
    I tried MaxSuperCD, and wasn't happy about it's inability to access
    directories on a CD with SPACES in - so I wrote my own.

Nowadays, I like to think that this door holds its own very well against, 
arguabley, the most popular CD Door out there (KewlCDPro).  OK, it may not
display the same number of files 'on screen',  but it has INDEX files, a 
SEARCH feature, 1024 Markable files, can view FILE_ID.DIZ, has ACCESS 
limited devices and displays accurate FILE SIZES.  Whats more it's FREE!!! 
    
    Come on Steve, the time to make KewlCDPro 'FREEWARE' is now!!! How can
    you continue to charge Ł5.00 for it??


    ALL coding by: No Frills [Dave Till]
    ANSI screens from various AMINET ansi art packs


    Coding Language Used: Amos Professional  
			  KewlDoors Amos Extension by Niki Murkett
			  Craft Extension for AMOS


    Other tools Used:     'LZX' - REGISTERED VERSION
                          'Find': Copyright Ralph Seichter
   			  'FlashFind 1.2': Copyright Frank Würkner

    Note that the REGISTERED 'LZX' is required, as this unpacks both LZX
    and LHA/LZH files - whereas the SHAREWARE LZX does not (used to extract
    'file_id.diz' from archives).
    
    FrillyCDPro uses the 'Find' program to generate it's INDEX files
        (Gets around problems with TILD signs and SPACES in DIRS/FILES)
    And it uses 'FlashFind' for its FAST searching routines.  

    All 'Extra' tools MUST go in your "C:" assign.

    
    The Documentation for these excellent tools can be found inside
    the "DOCS" directory.







                             @{"MAIN MENU" Link MAIN}


@endnode
@node SUGGESTIONS "Suggestions"
---<People who helped me out>---


       Users who have helped in the "coming together" of FrillyCDPro
       -------------------------------------------------------------

Ben Dover from Total Oblivion - suggested copying MARKED entries into
BBS:Tempfiles as soon as you MARK them instead of one-at-a-time at download
stage.  Resulted in a massive speed-up when it comes to downloading.  (NOW
UNUSED DUE TO POSSIBILITY OF 'LARGE' FILES ON A CD NOT FITTING ONTO
REMAINING H/D SPACE.....)

Steve Clack from Total Eclipse BBS (helped regarding the "proper" cursor
codes returned from a REMOTE user, as regards to those reported by a LOCAL
user.  My phone company (BT) salute your valiant efforts to keep my
chatting, above and beyond the call of duty ;-)

Colin Wilson from Phoenix BBS - mentioned how "sluggish" the 1.4.0 felt when
you scrolled up or down on either the FILES or DIRECTORYS.  So - I
seperated the routines, and managed to increase the speed 50% in the
process.  Also sent me an "improved" space-removal routine, which I changed
a bit - and incorported, in earlier versions.  I've now removed all the
space removal as it's NOT needed ;-) (found a better way to do it...)

Dunkie from Quest BBS - Spotted the "download" bug in the ORIGINAL 1.4.1
(this is on Amiga Format CD44 - DO NOT USE IT, IT IS BUGGED!!!!!!!)

Bippy M from Stingent BBS - Suggested FAR too many additions, (file sizes,
file comments, search engine etc....), and became cheif BETA-tester as a 
